Dynamic Programming (DP) in DSA

Dynamic Programming (DP) is an optimization technique used to solve problems by:

Breaking them into smaller subproblems

Solving each subproblem only once

Storing the result to avoid recomputation

🧠 When to Use DP?

A problem can be solved using DP if it has:

1️ -> Overlapping Subproblems

Same subproblems are solved multiple times.

Example: Fibonacci

fib(5) = fib(4) + fib(3)
fib(4) = fib(3) + fib(2)

Here fib(3) is calculated multiple times.

2️ ->  Optimal Substructure

Optimal solution of a problem depends on optimal solutions of subproblems.

Example:

Shortest Path

Knapsack

Coin Change

💡 Two Ways to Implement DP
1️ --> Top-Down (Memoization)

Recursion + storing results in array/map

Easier to write

Uses recursion stack

int dp[100];

int fib(int n) {
    if(n <= 1) return n;
    
    if(dp[n] != -1)
        return dp[n];
    
    return dp[n] = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
}

Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)

2️ -- > Bottom-Up (Tabulation)

Iterative

No recursion

Usually preferred in interviews

int fib(int n) {
    if(n <= 1) return n;
    
    int dp[n+1];
    dp[0] = 0;
    dp[1] = 1;
    
    for(int i = 2; i <= n; i++)
        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2];
    
    return dp[n];
}

Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)


